Lucidity — Licensing Map
========================

This repository contains code under multiple licenses. The license that
applies to each piece of code is determined by the directory it lives in.
Each licensed directory contains its own LICENSE file with the full text.

Quick reference:

  packages/mcp-server/         AGPL-3.0
  packages/shared/             AGPL-3.0
  packages/db/                 AGPL-3.0

  apps/api/                    Lucidity Commercial License (proprietary)
  apps/web/                    Lucidity Commercial License (proprietary)
  apps/mobile/                 Lucidity Commercial License (proprietary)

  packages/eslint-config/      MIT
  packages/typescript-config/  MIT

What this means in practice
---------------------------

The "runtime" pieces — the MCP server, the shared schemas/types, and the
database layer — are AGPL-3.0. You can self-host them, modify them, and
build on top of them, subject to AGPL's network-copyleft terms (any
service that exposes a modified version over the network must also publish
its source under AGPL).

The "product" pieces — the Hono API server, the Next.js web app, and the
Expo mobile app — are under the Lucidity Commercial License. You may read
them and run them locally for personal evaluation, but you may not operate
them as a service for others or use them in a commercial production
context without a separate commercial license.

The shared tooling configs (ESLint, TypeScript) are MIT, because configs
should be permissively licensed.

Why this structure
------------------

The intent is straightforward:

  1. Make the runtime auditable and self-hostable. If Lucidity will
     hold your wifi passwords and family photos, you should be able to
     read every line of code that handles them, and run your own copy
     if you want to.

  2. Reserve the hosted product. Running lucidity.today as a SaaS is
     the business model that funds development. A competitor building
     a Lucidity-clone hosted service is the one thing this licensing
     prevents.

  3. Keep configs friction-free.

This is the same pattern used by Cal.com, Sentry, Plausible, and PostHog
— a single monorepo with mixed licensing per folder.

